# Initialize a picture with bangladesh map, return objects used to make picture of climate data
# the param <size> donate the picture size
def picture_init(size = None):
    size = size or (16.0, 9.0)
    plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = size  # w h
    # plt.rcParams['figure.dpi'] = 500#(960, 720)  # w h
    fig = plt.figure()
    # plt.title('hourly_precipitation_of_bangladesh', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
    ax = plt.axes(projection=cartopy.crs.PlateCarree())
    ax.add_feature(cartopy.feature.LAND)
    ax.add_feature(cartopy.feature.OCEAN)
    ax.add_feature(cartopy.feature.COASTLINE)
    ax.add_feature(cartopy.feature.BORDERS, linestyle='-')
    ax.add_feature(cartopy.feature.LAKES, alpha=0.5)
#     print(x.shape,y.shape,tp[0].shape)
    text = ax.text(Grid['LonR'][0]+0.1, Grid['LatR'][1]-0.1, '', verticalalignment='top', fontsize=14, color='#67c164')
    norm = Normalize(vmin=Vmin, vmax=Vmax)
    mappable = ScalarMappable(norm=norm, cmap=PrecipCmap)
    cb = fig.colorbar(mappable, shrink=0.5)
    return fig, ax, text, cb

# make sure you had run <picture_init> before and set the returns as global variables, otherwice it will get wrong.
def make_picture(x, y, data, title = '', info = '', size =None, visible = True):
    global fig, ax, text, cb
    fig.set_visible(visible)
    ax.set_title(title, fontsize=14)
    p = ax.pcolor(x, y, data, cmap = PrecipCmap, transform = cartopy.crs.PlateCarree() )
#     if not cb:
#         cb = plt.colorbar(p, shrink=0.5)
#     else:
#         cb.update_normal(p)
    text.set_text(info)
#     plt.draw()
#     plt.show()

fig, ax, text, cb = picture_init()
make_picture(x, y, tp[0], title='Hourly Precipitation of Bangladesh\n', info=time[0].strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S'))

%matplotlib agg
# https://stackoverflow.com/questions/18717877/prevent-plot-from-showing-in-jupyter-notebook
# <x>, <y> and elements in <dataList> must have the same shape. <info> can be a str or a list with the same lenght as <dataList>
def make_gif(x, y, dataList, savePath, title = '', info = '', fps = 8, metadata=None):

    ndata = dataList.shape[0]
#     print(ndata)
    if isinstance(info, str):
        info = [info] * ndata
    else:
        assert len(info) == ndata, "lenght of info and dataList are not match."
    

    writer = anime.PillowWriter(fps=fps, metadata=metadata)
    
    with writer.saving(fig, savePath, 100):
        for n in range(ndata):
            make_picture(x, y, dataList[n], title=title, info=info[n])
#             ax.pcolor(x, y, tp[hour], cmap = 'RdYlBu_r', transform = cartopy.crs.PlateCarree() )
#             text.set_text(time[hour].strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S'))
            writer.grab_frame()
    fig.set_visible(False)
#     cb.remove()

Interpolation to Improve Resolution of data¶

In [13]:
# %matplotlib inline
# https://www.csdn.net/tags/MtjakgwsMDUyOC1ibG9n.html
# all interpolation method see https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/generated/scipy.interpolate.griddata.html
def interpolation(lon, lat, value, method='linear'): #  
    lon  = lon.copy()
    lat  = lat.copy()
    data = value.copy()

    lat_new, lon_new= np.mgrid [Grid['LatR'][0] : Grid['LatR'][1] : InterpolationResolution, Grid['LonR'][0] : Grid['LonR'][1] : InterpolationResolution] 
    # data = np.nanmean([tp[1]], axis = 0)
    # data = mean_tp
    # print(lat.shape, lon.shape)
    nlat=lat_new.shape[0]
    nlon=lat_new.shape[1]
    lons = np.tile(lon, lat.shape[0])
    lats = np.repeat(lat, lon.shape[0])
    points = np.stack([lons,lats],axis = -1)
    lon_new= lon_new.ravel()
    lat_new= lat_new.ravel()
    coord = np.stack([lon_new, lat_new],axis = -1)
    data = data.ravel()
    # print(data.shape, tp.shape, lons.shape, coord.shape)
    data_new = griddata(points, data, coord, method=method, fill_value=0, rescale=True) 
    data_new = data_new.reshape((nlat, nlon))
    data_new = data_new[::-1,:]
    lon_new = lon_new.reshape((nlat, nlon))
    lon_new = lon_new[::-1,:]
    lat_new = lat_new.reshape((nlat, nlon))
    lat_new = lat_new[::-1,:]
    return lon_new, lat_new, data_new

    # x_new, y_new = np.meshgrid(lon_new, lat_new)
#     print(lon_new.shape, lat_new.shape, data_new.shape)
#     print(data_new)

CDO example¶

CDO can be useful for some time processing. An example below shows how you can go from monthly values to yearly means:

Note : The '!' sign means its performed directly as command line operator

In [ ]:
!cdo yearmean /badc/cmip6/data/CMIP6/CMIP/MOHC/UKESM1-0-LL/historical/r1i1p1f2/Amon/tas/gn/latest/tas_Amon_UKESM1-0-LL_historical_r1i1p1f2_gn_195001-201412.nc tas_yearmean.nc

import matplotlib.animation as anime
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

fig = plt.figure()
l, = plt.plot([], [], 'k-')
l2, = plt.plot([], [], 'm--')
p1, = plt.plot([], [], 'ko')
p2, = plt.plot([], [], 'mo')
plt.xlabel('xlabel')
plt.ylabel('ylabel')
plt.title('title')

plt.xlim(-5, 5)
plt.ylim(-5, 5)


def func(x):
    return np.sin(x) * 3


def func2(x):
    return np.cos(x) * 3


metadata = dict(title="Movie", artist="sourabh")
writer = anime.PillowWriter(fps=15, metadata=metadata)

xlist = []
ylist = []
ylist2 = []
xlist2 = []
with writer.saving(fig, "sin+cosinewave.gif", 100):
    for xval in np.linspace(-5, 5, 100):
        xlist.append(xval)
        ylist.append(func(xval))

        l.set_data(xlist, ylist)
        l2.set_data(xlist2, ylist2)

        p1.set_data(xval, func(xval))

        writer.grab_frame()
    for xval in np.linspace(-5, 5, 100):
        xlist2.append(xval)
        ylist2.append(func2(xval))

        l.set_data(xlist, ylist)
        l2.set_data(xlist2, ylist2)

        p2.set_data(xval, func2(xval))

        writer.grab_frame()
